		<hr size="1">Ok, now you're just being silly.</P><P>Armies invading cities?  When was the last time an army of anything invaded anywhere in EQ?  Or was that just another over-extended "If EQ were real" analogy?  EQ is not real.  You can't cast a spell to get to the other side of the world.  You can't really compare economies since EQ has an unlimited source of income.  The real world doesn't have people who will buy any peice of junk you find laying on the ground.  It doesn't have caves full of monsters that automatically fills up even after you kill everything in sight.</P><P>As for the adventure, I already addressed that part, but you seemed to ignore it and simply restate your claim.  Adventurers in books may not teleport around much, but how often does it take two sentences for them to cross the continent?  It may take them two weeks, but the author doesn't describe all the mundane details because *that* would be boring.  He cuts to the action.</P><P>If you enjoy riding on a boat with nothing to do (can't even fish!), then more power to you.  Adventure away.  Me?  I'd prefer to get a group and go kill things.  Lazy?  No.  I've done my share of boat-riding and running cross-country pre-portal.  I don't play the game to waste my time with pointless tasks.  </P><P>"It takes time to build stuff."  Ok, if you want to use that logic, then that's why there weren't portals at the very beginning.  That's why there aren't portals all over Norath.</P><P>"Newbies dying because they took the wrong book."  Is that any different than a newbie getting killed in the middle of a desert with no idea where they are?  Both sound like the same kind of "adventure" to me.</P><P>If you dislike the portals so much (and you knew this was coming) -- don't use them.  But don't take them away for the other 95%+ that don't enjoy the monotony of long travel times.</P><P><BR>I've made my point.<BR>-- C.</P><P>EDIT:<BR>PS:  Let's use your real world analogy.  Say you work in New York and need to go to California.  Work is paying for it, so as far as you are concerned it is free.  Do you walk?  Ride a bike?  Drive?  No, you take a plane.  Lazy?  No.  Practical.  But just think of all the adventures you could have along the way and all the people you could meet in the small towns.  It doesn't matter.  You need to get to Cali and do your thing.  If there were a faster way, say a teleporter with a free, unlimited supply of energy, I'm sure you'd even use it.  Get to Cali, and then worry about having an adventure.</P><P>If you want a vacation/adventure, you can still do that, but don't eliminate airplanes for all the other people that still need a fast mode of transportation.</P><P>Ok, *now* I've had my say.<BR>-- C.</P><P></P><P>Message edited by: Cerpicio (9/25/2003 6:27:16 AM)<br>&nbsp;<br>&nbsp;<br></font>
